						<div class="postbody"><div class="quotetitle">Drag wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">I tried that technique before I went with the 4015 technique, and the problem I had with it was that it wouldn't silence the triangle channel immediately (there'd be a semirandom delay before it actually silenced the channel), and as such, it wasn't an acceptable solution for me.<br /></div>
<br />Writing $80 should turn the channel off immediately. I might be wrong, but I'm like 99% sure it does that, because any write with bit 7 set will load the lenght counter with the specified value, and if that's zero, then it's zero'd and the channel silcneces. When the bit 7 is clear I believe the lenght counter load itself on $4003 writes then decrease each tick - so write $00 to $4008 will work if it's followed by any $400b write.
<br />
<br />As tepples said, it's good to consider channel equals as much as possible. That's why you should one of the many techniques available to mute the channel - as long as it works and make your code simpler.
<br />
<br />Writing 0 then 1 to any $4015 bit will silent the channel (exept DPCM). Writing 0 force all lenght counters to 0, while writing 1 will just allow them to take any value for the next $4003/7/b/f write (n.b. those counters are rather useless I find).</div>

					
						<div class="postbody"><br />_________________<br />Life is complex: it has both real and imaginary components.</div>
